{
  "text": "Other variables recently identified to influence creatinine levels-merely studied in humans-are inter-and intra-subject variation including the moment of sampling (time of day), the age, the gender and racial factors [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Diet related factors can also affect USpG but with less impact compared to creatinine [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . The abrupt changes in appetite in these female pandas also considerably impact the total range observed between minimum and maximum values of USpG, however USpG remains within acceptable margins (Fig 2) . USpG is clearly less affected than creatinine, with USpG mainly indirectly altered by changes in hydration status and potentially also dietary composition. Creatinine on the other hand is directly influenced by increasing concentrations of reproductive hormones affecting activity rate and tissue turnover as well as nutritional intake. As a result, the use of creatinine as a correction factor may lead to falsely high (low creatine) or low (high creatine) hormone levels, as demonstrated in this study.",
  "correct_citation": {
